\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

experiment
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is to draw days from the year.
 There are 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{366}{180}$
\end_inset

 ways to draw 180 days from anywhere in the year for the 180 lottery tickets.
 In order that the days be evenly distributed there must be 
\begin_inset Formula $180/12=15$
\end_inset

 days chosen from each month.
 Then there are 
\begin_inset Formula $\underbrace{\binom{30}{15}^{4}\times\binom{31}{15}^{7}\times\binom{29}{15}}_{12}$
\end_inset

 ways to assign exactly 15 lottery tickets to each of the 12 months.
 Hence the probability of having all 180 lottery tickets evenly distributed
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\binom{30}{15}^{12}}{\binom{366}{180}}=.167\times10^{-8}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The experiment is again to draws days from the year.
 There are 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{336}{30}$
\end_inset

 ways to choose 30 days from all the days in the year that are not in September
 
\begin_inset Formula $(366-30=336)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{366}{30}$
\end_inset

 ways to choose 30 days from any of the days of the year.
 Hence the probability of not selecting any days from September is 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\binom{336}{30}/\binom{366}{30}=0.0686905$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

[1.23]
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

draw
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 has 4 possibilities: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \text{HH},\text{HT},\text{TH},\text{TT}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 So there are 
\begin_inset Formula $4^{n}$
\end_inset

 different outcomes of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

draws
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Then there are 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{n}{i}\binom{n}{i}$
\end_inset

 different each person could flip 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 heads, for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0,1,2,\cdots,n$
\end_inset

.
 Hence the probability of each person flipping the same number of heads
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=0}^{n}\binom{n}{i}^{2}/4^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 To see that this equals 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{2n}{n}/4^{n}$
\end_inset

 we prove Vandermonde's identity, namely that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\binom{m+n}{r}=\sum_{k=0}^{r}\binom{m}{k}\binom{n}{r-k}
\]

\end_inset

To see that this is the case take 2 urns, one with 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 red balls and one with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 green balls and consider how many collections of size 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 can be drawn from both urns.
 Certainly it's 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{m+n}{r}$
\end_inset

.
 But it's also the sum, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, of the number of collections with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 red balls and 
\begin_inset Formula $n-k$
\end_inset

 green balls.
 For fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 this is and thence follows Vandermonde's identity.
 Finally letting 
\begin_inset Formula $m=r=n$
\end_inset

 and using the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{n}{n-i}=\binom{n}{i}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{4^{n}}\sum_{i=0}^{n}\binom{n}{i}\binom{n}{i}=\frac{1}{4^{n}}\sum_{i=0}^{n}\binom{n}{i}\binom{n}{n-i}=\frac{1}{4^{n}}\binom{n+n}{n}=\frac{1}{4^{n}}\binom{2n}{n}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

[1.24]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Number of flips until heads is geometrically distributed, i.e.
 the probability that the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th flip is a head 
\begin_inset Formula $P(X=k)=(1-p)^{k-1}p$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1/2$
\end_inset

.
 The probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 wins is tantamount to the probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is odd (since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 flips first).
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(\text{A wins})=P(X=k=2i-1|i=1,2,3,\cdots)=\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}(1-p)^{(2i-1)-1}p=-\frac{(p-1)^{2}}{(1-p)^{2}(p-2)}
\]

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1/2$
\end_inset

 this is 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{(1/2-1)^{2}}{(1-1/2)^{2}(1/2-2)}=\frac{2}{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Simplifying the result from (a) we get that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(\text{A wins})=-\frac{(p-1)^{2}}{(1-p)^{2}(p-2)}=-\frac{(1-p)^{2}}{(1-p)^{2}(p-2)}=\frac{1}{2-p}=\frac{p}{2p-p^{2}}\frac{p}{1-(1-2p+p^{2})}=\frac{p}{1-(1-p)^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $P(\text{A wins})=\frac{1}{2-p}$
\end_inset

 we see that if 
\begin_inset Formula $0<p<1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}<P(\text{A wins})=\frac{1}{2-p}<1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

[1.26]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

Casts
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 until a 6 appears is geometrically distributed with 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1/6$
\end_inset

, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(X=k)=\bigg(1-\frac{1}{6}\bigg)^{k-1}\frac{1}{6}
\]

\end_inset

Computing the probability that one has to cast more than 5 times is tantamount
 to the complement of casting a 6 on either 1, 2, 3, 4, or 5 times.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(\text{casting more than 5 times)}=1-\sum_{k=1}^{5}\bigg(1-\frac{1}{6}\bigg)^{k-1}\frac{1}{6}=1-\bigg(\frac{1}{6}+\frac{5}{36}+\frac{25}{216}+\frac{125}{1296}+\frac{625}{7776}\bigg)=\frac{3125}{7776}=0.401878
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

[1.27]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Using pascal's rule
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=(1-1)^{n}=\sum_{k=0}^{n}\binom{n}{k}1^{n-k}(-1)^{k}=\sum_{k=0}^{n}(-1)^{k}\binom{n}{k}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
